actions.comment:
Thanks for the detailed explanation of your use case.

Skia (the underlying C++ library) removed indexed/palette-based color types (Index8) back in 2017, and has no support for sub-byte pixel formats like 1bpp, 2bpp, or 4bpp. All pixel formats in Skia use at least 8 bits per pixel. Since SkiaSharp wraps Skia, adding these formats would require changes to Skia's core rendering pipeline — which is outside our scope.

That said, you can achieve compact palette-based tile rendering at the application level:

```csharp
// Store your palette
var palette = new SKColor[16]; // 4bpp = 16 colors
palette[0] = SKColors.Black;
palette[1] = SKColors.Red;
// ...

// Store tile indices compactly (1 byte per pixel, or bit-pack for 4bpp)
byte[] tileIndices = new byte[8 * 8]; // 8x8 NES tile

// Expand to RGBA only when rendering
var info = new SKImageInfo(8, 8, SKColorType.Rgba8888, SKAlphaType.Premul);
using var bitmap = new SKBitmap(info);
unsafe
{
    var ptr = (uint*)bitmap.GetPixels();
    for (int i = 0; i < tileIndices.Length; i++)
        ptr[i] = (uint)palette[tileIndices[i]];
}
bitmap.NotifyPixelsChanged();
canvas.DrawBitmap(bitmap, destX, destY);
```

For sub-byte packing (4bpp/2bpp), you can pack multiple indices per byte in your storage format and unpack only when expanding to the render buffer. This keeps your binary storage compact while using SkiaSharp's standard rendering path.

For a NES/SNES-style tile system with 65K+ tiles, consider maintaining a small render buffer and only expanding the visible tiles each frame — the expansion cost for 8×8 tiles is negligible.

See also #568 (the Skia M61 update that removed Index8) and #2383 (similar discussion about non-standard pixel formats).
